Drawing boundaries on a diagram is easy. Keeping them in code under deadline pressure is where most projects fail.

We now have five bounded contexts talking to each other through facades, domain events, and shared kernel IDs. The patterns are all in place. The question isn’t whether these boundaries are a good idea — it’s whether they’ll still exist six months from now.
Boundaries erode in small, reasonable-looking steps. Someone needs a product name in the cart, so they import CatalogProduct directly. Someone needs the cart total in checkout, so they reach into cart's internal state selectors. Each import feels justified in the moment. Six months later, every module depends on every other module, and you're back where you started.
Good architecture doesn’t rely on team discipline alone. It uses tooling to make violations visible — before they merge.

The Folder Structure
Each bounded context maps to a top-level directory with four internal layers:
src/app/
│
├── shared-kernel/
│ ├── value-objects/
│ ├── errors/
│ ├── entity.base.ts
│ ├── result.ts
│ ├── domain-event-bus.ts
│ └── index.ts ← Public API
│
├── catalog/
│ ├── domain/ ← Entities, Value Objects, Repository interface
│ ├── application/ ← Facade
│ ├── infrastructure/ ← HTTP repository, mapper
│ ├── presentation/ ← Components
│ └── index.ts ← Public API
│
├── cart/
├── checkout/
├── orders/
├── profile/
│
└── app.routes.tsThe dependency direction inside each context is: presentation → application → domain ← infrastructure.
The domain layer imports nothing above it. Infrastructure imports the domain (to implement repository interfaces) but is never imported by presentation or application. This single rule — enforced by the folder structure — keeps each context layered and testable.

The index.ts Barrel: Your Public API Contract
Every bounded context publishes exactly what other contexts are allowed to use — and nothing more:
// catalog/index.ts
export { CatalogFacade } from './application/catalog.facade';
export { ProductCardComponent } from './presentation/product-card/product-card.component';
export { ProductListComponent } from './presentation/product-list/product-list.component';// These are private - never export:
// CatalogProduct ← internal domain model
// ProductApiRepository ← infrastructure detail
// ProductMapper ← infrastructure detail
// cart/index.ts
export { CartFacade } from './application/cart.facade';
export { CartDrawerComponent } from './presentation/cart-drawer/cart-drawer.component';
export { CartDomainEvents } from './domain/events/cart-domain.events';
If it’s not in index.ts, it's private. Any import that goes deeper than the barrel file is a boundary violation.

NgModule and Standalone Components
Both approaches work. The discipline is the same.
NgModule
// catalog/catalog.module.ts
@NgModule({
imports: [CommonModule, SharedKernelModule, RouterModule.forChild(catalogRoutes)],
declarations: [ProductCardComponent, ProductListComponent, ProductDetailComponent],
exports: [ProductCardComponent, ProductListComponent],
providers: [
CatalogFacade,
CatalogMapper,
{ provide: ProductRepository, useClass: ProductApiRepository },
]
})
export class CatalogModule {}NgModule.exports gives a second enforcement layer — anything not exported isn't accessible from outside even if someone tries.
Standalone Components (Angular 17+)
@Component({
selector: 'shopflow-product-card',
standalone: true,
imports: [RouterLink, MoneyFormatPipe],
templateUrl: './product-card.component.html',
})
export class ProductCardComponent {
@Input() product!: CatalogProduct;
}With standalone components there’s no NgModule.exports safety net. The barrel file becomes the only gatekeeper — which means ESLint boundary rules are no longer optional.

Lazy Loading Aligned With Bounded Contexts
Each bounded context should lazy-load as a natural unit. The router boundary and the context boundary should coincide:
// app.routes.ts
export const appRoutes: Routes = [
{
path: '',
loadChildren: () =>
import('./catalog/catalog.routes').then(m => m.catalogRoutes),
},
{
path: 'cart',
loadChildren: () =>
import('./cart/cart.routes').then(m => m.cartRoutes),
},
{
path: 'checkout',
loadChildren: () =>
import('./checkout/checkout.routes').then(m => m.checkoutRoutes),
},
{
path: 'orders',
loadChildren: () =>
import('./orders/orders.routes').then(m => m.ordersRoutes),
canActivate: [AuthGuard],
},
];This isn’t just a performance win. It’s an architectural signal: a context that can’t lazy-load independently is too coupled to something else. If removing the lazy boundary causes a compile error, you’ve found a boundary violation worth fixing.

Enforcing Boundaries With ESLint
npm install --save-dev eslint-plugin-boundaries// .eslintrc.js
module.exports = {
plugins: ['boundaries'],
settings: {
'boundaries/elements': [
{ type: 'shared-kernel', pattern: 'src/app/shared-kernel/*' },
{ type: 'catalog', pattern: 'src/app/catalog/*' },
{ type: 'cart', pattern: 'src/app/cart/*' },
{ type: 'checkout', pattern: 'src/app/checkout/*' },
{ type: 'orders', pattern: 'src/app/orders/*' },
{ type: 'profile', pattern: 'src/app/profile/*' },
],
},
rules: {
'boundaries/element-types': ['error', {
default: 'disallow',
rules: [
{ from: '*', allow: ['shared-kernel'] },
{ from: 'cart', allow: ['catalog'] },
{ from: 'checkout', allow: ['cart', 'catalog'] },
{ from: 'profile', allow: ['shared-kernel'] },
{ from: 'orders', allow: ['shared-kernel'] },
]
}]
}
};This import now fails immediately at lint:
// ❌ orders/presentation/order-detail.component.ts
import { CatalogProduct } from '../catalog/domain/catalog-product.entity';
// ESLint Error: 'orders' is not allowed to import from 'catalog'No code review needed. No relying on someone noticing. The violation fails at ng lint — or in the editor in real time.

Nx: Even Stronger Enforcement
In an Nx monorepo, contexts become libraries with tags. Constraint enforcement happens at the dependency graph level — not just lint:
// libs/catalog/project.json
{ "tags": ["scope:catalog", "type:feature"] }// libs/shared-kernel/project.json
{ "tags": ["scope:shared", "type:domain"] }// nx.json
{
"depConstraints": [
{ "sourceTag": "scope:shared", "onlyDependOnLibsWithTags": ["scope:shared"] },
{ "sourceTag": "scope:catalog", "onlyDependOnLibsWithTags": ["scope:shared"] },
{ "sourceTag": "scope:cart", "onlyDependOnLibsWithTags": ["scope:shared", "scope:catalog"] },
{ "sourceTag": "scope:checkout", "onlyDependOnLibsWithTags": ["scope:shared", "scope:catalog", "scope:cart"] }
]
}nx graph then visualizes the actual dependency graph. You can see at a glance whether contexts are leaking into each other.

The Three Clean Ways Contexts Communicate
With strict boundaries, contexts still need to talk. There are exactly three patterns — all of which we’ve already used:
Facades — for data queries. Cart needs a product name? Call CatalogFacade.getProductsByIds(). No domain class crossing.
Domain Events — for reactions. Checkout completes, Cart publishes CartCheckedOut. Orders, Analytics, and Loyalty each subscribe independently. Zero direct dependencies.
Shared Kernel types — for IDs. ProductId lives in the shared kernel. Both Catalog and Cart use it without importing from each other.
Anything else is a boundary violation. If you find yourself needing it, the context map needs revisiting — not the ESLint rule.

Key Takeaways
The four-layer folder structure (presentation → application → domain ← infrastructure) enforces the right dependency direction inside every context.
Barrel files are the public API contract. If it’s not exported from index.ts, it's private.
ESLint boundary rules make boundary violations a build failure — not a code review comment that gets missed.
A context that can’t lazy-load independently is a context that’s too coupled.
Cross-context communication has exactly three clean patterns: facades, domain events, shared kernel IDs.

